267","1277":"1277","1211":"1211","1265":"1265","about 1267":"about 1267","1219":"1219","Brandeston, Suffolk, England":"Brandeston, Suffolk, England","Blaxhall, Suffolk, England":"Blaxhall, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","France":"France","Blaxhall, Plomesgate, Suffolk, England":"Blaxhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weyland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: variant of   Wieland  .","English: variant of   Wayland  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wieland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Otto, Heinz, Dieter, Dietrich, Erdmann, Florian, Franz, Fritz, Gerhard.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wīg</i> ‘war’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’. This name was borne by the supernaturally skilled smith of ancient Germanic folk legend, and for this reason it may in part have been given as a nickname to blacksmiths.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): presumably an adoption of the German surname."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Weyland II was born in 1230, in Blaxhall, Suffolk, England, his father, John de Weyland, was 12 and his mother, Mrs. Mary de Weyland, was 19. He married Anne de Coleville. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1291, in France, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1230–1291":"1230–1291","1241–1274":"1241–1274","1240–1277":"1240–1277","1260–1312":"1260–1312","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1267–1327":"1267–1327","1219–1274":"1219–1274","1211–Female":"1211–Surnud","1230":"1230","1274":"1274","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1259":"1259","about 1239":"umbes 1239","1312":"1312","1267":"1267","1277":"1277","1211":"1211","1265":"1265","about 1267":"umbes 1267","1219":"1219","Brandeston, Suffolk, England":"Brandeston, Suffolk, England","Blaxhall, Suffolk, England":"Blaxhall, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","France":"Prantsusmaa","Blaxhall, Plomesgate, Suffolk, England":"Blaxhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa,